# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: visual-question-answering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:visual-question-answering/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:visual-question-answering/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:visual-question-answering/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Multimodal learning was proposed in 2011 at the beginning of the deep learning period.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Large multimodal models, such as Google Gemini and GPT-4o, have become increasingly popular since 2023, enabling increased versatility and a broader understanding of real-world phenomena.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Data usually comes with different modalities which carry different information.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] For example, it is very common to caption an image to convey the information not presented in the image itself.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Similarly, sometimes it is more straightforward to use an image to describe information which may not be obvious from text.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] As a result, if different words appear in similar images, then these words likely describe the same thing.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Conversely, if a word is used to describe seemingly dissimilar images, then these images may represent the same object.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Thus, in cases dealing with multi-modal data, it is important to use a model which is able to jointly represent the information such that the model can capture the combined information from different modalities.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Models such as CLIP (Contrastive Language–Image Pretraining) learn joint representations of images and text by optimizing contrastive objectives, allowing the model to match images with their corresponding textual descriptions.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] A Boltzmann machine is a type of stochastic neural network invented by Geoffrey Hinton and Terry Sejnowski in 1985.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Boltzmann machines can be seen as the stochastic, generative counterpart of Hopfield nets.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] They are named after the Boltzmann distribution in statistical mechanics.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] The units in Boltzmann machines are divided into two groups: visible units and hidden units.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Each unit is like a neuron with a binary output that represents whether it is activated or not.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] General Boltzmann machines allow connection between any units.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] However, learning is impractical using general Boltzmann Machines because the computational time is exponential to the size of the machine.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] A more efficient architecture is called restricted Boltzmann machine where connection is only allowed between hidden unit and visible unit, which is described in the next section.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] Multimodal deep Boltzmann machines can process and learn from different types of information, such as images and text, simultaneously.
[src:visual-question-answering/multimodal-learning] This can notably be done by having a separate deep Boltzmann machine for each modality, for example one for images and one for text, joined at an additional top hidden layer.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] A question-answering implementation, usually a computer program, may construct its answers by querying a structured database of knowledge or information, usually a knowledge base.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] More commonly, question-answering systems can pull answers from an unstructured collection of natural language documents.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Some examples of natural language document collections used for question answering systems include reference texts, compiled newswire reports, Wikipedia pages and other World Wide Web pages.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Two early question answering systems were BASEBALL and LUNAR.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] BASEBALL answered questions about Major League Baseball over a period of one year.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] LUNAR answered questions about the geological analysis of rocks returned by the Apollo Moon missions.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Both question answering systems were very effective in their chosen domains.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] LUNAR was demonstrated at a lunar science convention in 1971 and it was able to answer 90% of the questions in its domain that were posed by people untrained on the system.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Further restricted-domain question answering systems were developed in the following years.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The common feature of all these systems is that they had a core database or knowledge system that was hand-written by experts of the chosen domain.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The language abilities of BASEBALL and LUNAR used techniques similar to ELIZA and DOCTOR, the first chatterbot programs.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] SHRDLU was a successful question-answering program developed by Terry Winograd in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] It simulated the operation of a robot in a toy world (the "blocks world"), and it offered the possibility of asking the robot questions about the state of the world.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The strength of this system was the choice of a very specific domain and a very simple world with rules of physics that were easy to encode in a computer program.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] In the 1970s, knowledge bases were developed that targeted narrower domains of knowledge.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The question answering systems developed to interface with these expert systems produced more repeatable and valid responses to questions within an area of knowledge.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] These expert systems closely resembled modern question answering systems except in their internal architecture.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Expert systems rely heavily on expert-constructed and organized knowledge bases, whereas many modern question answering systems rely on statistical processing of a large, unstructured, natural language text corpus.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The 1970s and 1980s saw the development of comprehensive theories in computational linguistics, which led to the development of ambitious projects in text comprehension and question answering.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] One example was the Unix Consultant (UC), developed by Robert Wilensky at U.C.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The system answered questions pertaining to the Unix operating system.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] It had a comprehensive, hand-crafted knowledge base of its domain, and it aimed at phrasing the answer to accommodate various types of users.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Another project was LILOG, a text-understanding system that operated on the domain of tourism information in a German city.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The systems developed in the UC and LILOG projects never went past the stage of simple demonstrations, but they helped the development of theories on computational linguistics and reasoning.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Specialized natural-language question answering systems have been developed, such as EAGLi for health and life scientists.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] In 2011, Watson, a question answering computer system developed by IBM, competed in two exhibition matches of *Jeopardy!* against Brad Rutter and Ken Jennings, winning by a significant margin.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Facebook Research made their DrQA system available under an open source license.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] This system uses Wikipedia as knowledge source.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The open source framework Haystack by deepset combines open-domain question answering with generative question answering and supports the domain adaptation of the underlying language models for industry use cases.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Large Language Models (LLMs)[36] like GPT-4[37], Gemini[38] are examples of successful QA systems that are enabling more sophisticated understanding and generation of text.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] When coupled with Multimodal[39] QA Systems, which can process and understand information from various modalities like text, images, and audio, LLMs significantly improve the capabilities of QA systems.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Question-answering research attempts to develop ways of answering a wide range of question types, including fact, list, definition, how, why, hypothetical, semantically constrained, and cross-lingual questions.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Another way to categorize question-answering systems is by the technical approach used.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Rule-based systems use a set of rules to determine the correct answer to a question.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Statistical systems use statistical methods to find the most likely answer to a question.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Hybrid systems use a combination of rule-based and statistical methods.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] As of 2001, question-answering systems typically included a *question classifier* module that determined the type of question and the type of answer.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Different types of question-answering systems employ different architectures.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] For example, modern open-domain question answering systems may use a retriever-reader architecture.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The retriever is aimed at retrieving relevant documents related to a given question, while the reader is used to infer the answer from the retrieved documents.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Systems such as GPT-3, T5, and BART use an end-to-end architecture in which a transformer-based architecture stores large-scale textual data in the underlying parameters.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Such models can answer questions without accessing any external knowledge sources.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Question answering is dependent on a good search corpus; without documents containing the answer, there is little any question answering system can do.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Larger collections generally mean better question answering performance, unless the question domain is orthogonal to the collection.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Correct answers can be filtered from false positives because the system can rely on versions of the correct answer appearing more times in the corpus than incorrect ones.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Some question answering systems rely heavily on automated reasoning.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] In information retrieval, an open-domain question answering system tries to return an answer in response to the user's question.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The returned answer is in the form of short texts rather than a list of relevant documents.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The system finds answers by using a combination of techniques from computational linguistics, information retrieval, and knowledge representation.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The system takes a natural language question as an input rather than a set of keywords, for example: "When is the national day of China?" It then transforms this input sentence into a query in its logical form.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Accepting natural language questions makes the system more user-friendly, but harder to implement, as there are a variety of question types and the system will have to identify the correct one in order to give a sensible answer.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Assigning a question type to the question is a crucial task; the entire answer extraction process relies on finding the correct question type and hence the correct answer type.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Keyword extraction is the first step in identifying the input question type.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] In some cases, words clearly indicate the question type, e.g., "Who", "Where", "When", or "How many"—these words might suggest to the system that the answers should be of type "Person", "Location", "Date", or "Number", respectively.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] POS (part-of-speech) tagging and syntactic parsing techniques can also determine the answer type.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] In the example above, the subject is "Chinese National Day", the predicate is "is" and the adverbial modifier is "when", therefore the answer type is "Date".
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Unfortunately, some interrogative words like "Which", "What", or "How" do not correspond to unambiguous answer types: Each can represent more than one type.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] In situations like this, other words in the question need to be considered.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] A lexical dictionary such as WordNet can be used for understanding the context.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Once the system identifies the question type, it uses an information retrieval system to find a set of documents that contain the correct keywords.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] A tagger and NP/Verb Group chunker can verify whether the correct entities and relations are mentioned in the found documents.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] For questions such as "Who" or "Where", a named-entity recogniser finds relevant "Person" and "Location" names from the retrieved documents.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Only the relevant paragraphs are selected for ranking.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] A vector space model can classify the candidate answers.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Check if the answer is of the correct type as determined in the question type analysis stage.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] An inference technique can validate the candidate answers.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] A score is then given to each of these candidates according to the number of question words it contains and how close these words are to the candidate—the more and the closer the better.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The answer is then translated by parsing into a compact and meaningful representation.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] An open-source, math-aware, question answering system called MathQA, based on Ask Platypus and Wikidata, was published in 2018.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] MathQA takes an English or Hindi natural language question as input and returns a mathematical formula retrieved from Wikidata as a succinct answer, translated into a computable form that allows the user to insert values for the variables.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The system retrieves names and values of variables and common constants from Wikidata if those are available.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] It is claimed that the system outperforms a commercial computational mathematical knowledge engine on a test set.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] MathQA is hosted by Wikimedia at https://mathqa.wmflabs.org/.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] In 2022, it was extended to answer 15 math question types.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] MathQA methods need to combine natural and formula language.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] One possible approach is to perform supervised annotation via Entity Linking.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The "ARQMath Task" at CLEF 2020 was launched to address the problem of linking newly posted questions from the platform Math Stack Exchange to existing ones that were already answered by the community.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Providing hyperlinks to already answered, semantically related questions helps users to get answers earlier but is a challenging problem because semantic relatedness is not trivial.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The lab was motivated by the fact that 20% of mathematical queries in general-purpose search engines are expressed as well-formed questions.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The challenge contained two separate sub-tasks.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Task 1: "Answer retrieval" matching old post answers to newly posed questions, and Task 2: "Formula retrieval" matching old post formulae to new questions.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Starting with the domain of mathematics, which involves formula language, the goal is to later extend the task to other domains (e.g., STEM disciplines, such as chemistry, biology, etc.), which employ other types of special notation (e.g., chemical formulae).
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The inverse of mathematical question answering—mathematical question generation—has also been researched.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The PhysWikiQuiz physics question generation and test engine retrieves mathematical formulae from Wikidata together with semantic information about their constituting identifiers (names and values of variables).
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] The formulae are then rearranged to generate a set of formula variants.
[src:visual-question-answering/question-answering] Subsequently, the variables are substituted with random values to generate a large number of different questions suitable for individual student tests.
